content:
We need to analyze case: recurrent fever, serositis (abdominal pain, chest pain with breathing difficulty suggests pleuritis), arthritis (knees, ankles), Mediterranean descent, autosomal dominant family history, onset childhood, periodic attacks every 2-3 weeks, labs show inflammation, asymptomatic between attacks. This is classic Familial Mediterranean Fever (FMF). Genetic testing pending (MEFV gene). So primary diagnosis FMF.

Differential: other autoinflammatory periodic fever syndromes: TRAPS (TNF receptor-associated periodic syndrome) (though more prolonged episodes, periorbital edema), Hyper-IgD syndrome (Mevalonate kinase deficiency) (episodes last days to weeks, often with GI pain), Cryopyrin-associated periodic syndromes (CAPS) e.g., Muckle-Wells (but includes urticaria, hearing loss), PFAPA (periodic fever, aphthous stomatitis, pharyngitis, adenitis) (but age of onset younger, no serositis). Also consider systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) but not periodic and family history.

Thus diff list 3-5.

Key findings: recurrent fever, serositis, arthritis, Mediterranean descent, autosomal dominant pattern, onset childhood, normal between attacks, elevated acute-phase reactants.

Tests: Genetic testing for MEFV (priority urgent? maybe routine but due to suspicion, high priority). Serum amyloid A (SAA) to assess risk for amyloidosis. Complete blood count, CRP, ESR (already done). Urinalysis for proteinuria (amyloidosis). Imaging if needed (abdominal ultrasound, chest X-ray). Also rule out other periodic fever syndromes: TNFRSF1A sequencing, MVK gene testing.

Management: Immediate: treat acute attack with NSAIDs, colchicine prophylaxis (primary therapy). For colchicine-resistant, consider IL-1 inhibitors (anakinra, canakinumab). Also advise vaccinations, lifestyle.

Medications: Colchicine 1.0-2.0 mg daily divided (e.g., 0.5 mg twice daily) oral; NSAID ibuprofen 400-600 mg q6-8h PRN; For acute severe chest/abdominal pain maybe analgesics.

Consultations: Rheumatology (urgent), Genetics (routine), Nephrology (if amylo). Also possibly gastroenterology.

Red flags: Development of amyloidosis (proteinuria, renal failure), persistent high inflammatory markers between attacks, severe uncontrolled attacks, signs of pericardial tamponade, etc.

Now produce JSON with required fields.

Make sure confidence for primary high 0.95.

Differential list 4 items with confidence values: TRAPS 0.4, Hyper-IgD syndrome 0.35, CAPS (Muckle-Wells) 0.30, PFAPA 0.25. Provide ICD-10 codes: FMF M04.1? Actually FMF is M04.1 "Familial Mediterranean fever". TRAPS is M04.8 "Other autoinflammatory syndromes". Hyper-IgD syndrome: M04.8 also? Might use E85.0 for amyloidosis? For hyper-IgD, could be D68.1 "Hereditary deficiency of complement components"? Not exact. Use ICD-10 code: D80.0? Not correct. Might use "D68.8 Other specified coagulation disorders". Better to use "D80.0" for "Immunodeficiency with predominantly antibody defects"? Not great. Use generic code: M04.8 for FMF? Actually M04 is "Reactive arthropathies". M04.1 is FMF. For TRAPS: M04.8. For Hyper-IgD syndrome: D68.9 (Disorder of coagulation, unspecified) not appropriate. Better use "E88.0" for "Disorder of amino-acid metabolism"? Not. Use "M04.8" for "Other periodic fever syndromes". Use "M04.8" for CAPS too. Anyway include best possible.

